  "prompt": "Is money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. **Money laundering** is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through a complex sequence of banking or commercial transactions, to make it appear as though it came from a legitimate source.\n\n### Why is Money Laundering Illegal?\n1. **Criminal Activity**: It often involves funds derived from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or organized crime.\n2. **Economic Harm**: It destabilizes financial systems, undermines the integrity of financial institutions, and can distort economies.\n3. **Facilitation of Crime**: By allowing criminals to \"clean\" their money, it enables further illegal activities.\n\n### Legal Consequences\nMoney laundering is a serious criminal offense punishable by:\n- Heavy fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n purchased with laundered money may be seized.\n\n### Global Efforts to Combat Money Laundering\nMany countries have laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering, and international organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CFT) efforts. Financial institutions are required to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities, such as know-your-customer (KYC) procedures and transaction monitoring.",
